======================================================================
NAIVE FORMULA: g_k^naive(m) = Σ C(k-1,r-1)·C(m,r)·2^{r-1}
======================================================================
  k=3: naive leading = 2/3/m^3, true leading = 2/3/m³
  k=4: naive leading = 1/3/m^4, true leading = 10/3/m³
    correction must kill the m^4 term: -2^{3}/4! = -1/3
  k=5: naive leading = 2/15/m^5, true leading = 388/3/m³
    correction must kill the m^5 term: -2^{4}/5! = -2/15
  k=6: naive leading = 2/45/m^6, true leading = 23220/m³
    correction must kill the m^6 term: -2^{5}/6! = -2/45
  k=7: naive leading = 4/315/m^7, true leading = 19826270/3/m³
    correction must kill the m^7 term: -2^{6}/7! = -4/315
  k=8: naive leading = 1/315/m^8, true leading = 7309726742/3/m³
    correction must kill the m^8 term: -2^{7}/8! = -1/315
  k=9: naive leading = 2/2835/m^9, true leading = 3262687720240/3/m³
    correction must kill the m^9 term: -2^{8}/9! = -2/2835

======================================================================
EGF OF NAIVE FORMULA
======================================================================
g_k^naive(m) = Σ C(k-1,r-1)·C(m,r)·2^{r-1}
= coefficient of t^{k-1} in (1+t)^{k-1} summed with C(m,r)·2^{r-1}

Using the identity Σ_r C(m,r)·z^r = (1+z)^m:
  Σ_{r≥1} C(m,r)·2^{r-1} = ((1+2)^m - 1)/2 = (3^m - 1)/2
  But we also sum over compositions, so it's not just 3^m.

Actually: g_k^naive(m) = Σ_r C(k-1,r-1)·C(m,r)·2^{r-1}
= (1/2) Σ_r C(k-1,r-1)·C(m,r)·2^r
Let u^r replace 2^r, we get:
Σ_r C(k-1,r-1)·C(m,r)·u^r = u·Σ_r C(k-1,r)·C(m,r+1)·u^r

Numerical check of naive = binomial sum:
  k=4, m=3: naive=33, 3^m=13
  k=4, m=5: naive=225, 3^m=121
  k=4, m=7: naive=833, 3^m=1093
  k=5, m=3: naive=51, 3^m=13
  k=5, m=5: naive=501, 3^m=121
  k=5, m=7: naive=2471, 3^m=1093

